                                      muKern v.1.0.062026

A minimal microkernel design for x86_64, ARMv8-A and RV64, 
plus a working proof-of-concept that boots on all three
and drops you into a tiny serial REPL.

ROADMAP

-----------------------------
PHASE 1 : Foundation
-----------------------------

Goal: Boot the kernel on x86_64, and print to the screen. 
Focus: arch/*/boot, Basic kernel/main.c.

M1a: The "Hello World" Boot

        Implement header.S and loader.S to switch CPU to 64-bit long mode.
        Set up a minimal stack.
        Jump to a C function kmain().
        Success Criteria: QEMU boots and prints "Kernel Started" to the serial console or VGA.

M1b: Basic Interrupt Handling

        Implement the Interrupt Descriptor Table (IDT).
        Handle a timer interrupt (e.g., PIT or HPET).
        Success Criteria: A counter increments in the interrupt handler and prints a dot . 
        every second.


-----------------------------
PHASE 2: Concurrency & Memory
-----------------------------
Goal: Run multiple threads and manage physical memory. 
Focus: kernel/sched.c, kernel/vm.c, arch/*/mm.


M2a: Physical Memory Allocator

        Implement a simple "Bump Allocator" or "Bitmap" to track free RAM frames.
        Success Criteria: Kernel can allocate and free physical pages without crashing. 

M2b: Virtual Memory & Paging

        Set up page tables (4-level paging for x86_64).
        Enable the MMU.
        Success Criteria: Kernel runs entirely in virtual memory; accessing unmapped
        addresses triggers a controlled fault. 

M2c: Preemptive Multitasking

        Implement struct thread and a Run Queue.
        Write the context switch code (switch_to) in assembly (save/restore registers).
        Configure the timer to trigger a scheduler tick.
        Success Criteria: Two kernel threads print "A" and "B" alternately,
        preempting each other automatically. 

-----------------------------
PHASE 3: The Microkernel Core (IPC)
-----------------------------

Goal: Implement the defining feature of a microkernel: Inter-Process Communication. 
Focus: kernel/ipc.c, kernel/cap.c.

M3a: Synchronous IPC Mechanism

        Implement send(thread_id, message) and receive(thread_id).
        Sender blocks until receiver is ready (Rendezvous).
        Pass data via registers (optimization) or kernel stack.
        Success Criteria: Two kernel threads exchange a integer value successfully. 

M3b: Capability-Based Security

        Implement a Capability Table (CTable) for each thread.
        Restrict IPC: Thread A can only message Thread B if it holds a capability.
        Success Criteria: A thread without a capability fails to send a message; access is denied.

M3c: User Mode Entry

        Create a mechanism to load a binary into memory and switch CPU privilege level (Ring 3 / EL0).
        Implement a syscall trap entry/exit.
        Success Criteria: A minimal user-space program runs, executes a syscall, and exits cleanly. 


-----------------------------
PHASE 4: User-Space Servers
-----------------------------

Goal: Move logic out of the kernel. The kernel is now frozen; 
all new features go to servers/. Focus: servers/init, servers/pm, lib/.

M4a: The Init Server

    Build a static binary init that the kernel loads first.
    init creates the root capability space and spawns the next server.
    Success Criteria: Kernel boots, loads init from rootfs, and jumps to it. Kernel is now idle.

M4b: Process Manager (PM)

    Implement a user-space server that handles create_thread and destroy_thread requests via IPC.
    Success Criteria: init asks PM to spawn a "Hello World" user process.

M4c: External Page Fault Handler

    Remove page-fault logic from the kernel.
    Kernel sends IPC to a vm_server on fault.
    Success Criteria: A user process allocates memory dynamically; the VM server maps 
    pages on demand. 

PHASE 5: Drivers & Filesystem

Goal: A usable system with disk I/O and files. Focus: drivers/, servers/fs_server.

M5a: User-Space Console Driver

    Move UART/VGA code to a user-space driver.
    Other servers send IPC messages to print text.
    Success Criteria: init prints to screen by messaging the Console Driver.

M5b: Block Device Driver

    Implement a simple IDE/VirtIO driver in user space.
    Success Criteria: Can read raw sectors from the virtual disk via IPC.

M5c: Filesystem Server

    Implement a simple VFS and filesystem (e.g., TAR or simple FS) in fs_server.
    Success Criteria: A user program can open() and read() a file by messaging the FS server. 


-----------------------------
PHASE 6: Porting & Hardening
-----------------------------

Goal: Prove the design is robust and portable.

M6a: ARM64 Port

        Replicate Phase 1-3 for arch/arm64.
        Success Criteria: System boots in QEMU ARM64.

M6b: RISC-V Port

        Replicate Phase 1-3 for arch/riscv64.
        Success Criteria: System boots in QEMU RISC-V.

M6c: Crash Recovery

        Kill a driver intentionally.             
        Success Criteria: The init or monitor server detects the death and restarts the 
        driver without rebooting the kernel.

Start with Phase 1 on x86_64. Do not attempt to support multiple architectures until Phase 6. 
Keep the kernel code in kernel/ strictly under 5,000 lines. 
If you find yourself adding logic there, stop and move it to servers/. 
